---
/**
 * /case-studies/china-backbone — Beijing–Shanghai QKD trunk.
 *
 * The longest deployed terrestrial QKD network. Trusted-node prepare-and-measure
 * — the contrast point for entanglement-based deployments like EPB and Knaut.
 */
import Infographic from "../../layouts/Infographic.astro";
import Center from "../../components/Center.astro";
import Stack from "../../components/Stack.astro";
import SiteNav from "../../components/SiteNav.astro";
import SourceNote from "../../components/SourceNote.astro";
import { url } from "../../lib/url";

const sections = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Overview" },
  { id: "what",     label: "What it is" },
  { id: "papers",   label: "Published papers" },
  { id: "verified", label: "Verified claims" },
  { id: "caveats",  label: "Things to note" },
  { id: "related",  label: "Related entries" },
];

// Published-paper lineage for the Beijing–Shanghai backbone and its
// predecessor metro networks. All links are trusted-relay decoy-state BB84;
// the trust model does not vary across rows so no trust column is shown.
// `inYaml` = true when the id already exists in sources.yaml and SourceNote
// can be rendered; false for new ids pending addition to sources.yaml.
const papers = [
  {
    year: "2009",
    ref: "chen-optexpress-17-2009",
    inYaml: true,
    paper: "Chen et al., Opt. Express 17.6540",
    result: "4-node Hefei field trial over 20 km of dark fibre; decoy-state BB84 with WDM co-existing traffic.",
    implies: "First Chinese multi-node QKD field demonstration — validated that decoy-BB84 survives a live metropolitan fibre plant and sets the hardware template for the backbone nodes.",
  },
  {
    year: "2010",
    ref: "chen-optexpress-18-2010",
    inYaml: true,
    paper: "Chen et al., Opt. Express 18.27217",
    result: "8-node Hefei metropolitan all-pass network plus a 67 km inter-city link to Wuhu; any-to-any QKD routing.",
    implies: "Demonstrated the any-to-any trusted-relay topology and optical-switch routing that the four-city trunk would later scale up.",
  },
  {
    year: "2021",
    ref: "chen-npjqi-7-2021",
    inYaml: true,
    paper: "Chen et al., npj QI 7.134",
    result: "46-node Hefei metropolitan QAN on commercial fibre; 31-month continuous operation.",
    implies: "Showed that a trusted-relay QKD mesh sustains production-grade uptime and is maintainable with standard telecom tooling — the metropolitan layer that the backbone trunk terminates into.",
  },
  {
    year: "2021",
    ref: "chen-natphoton-2021-jingu",
    inYaml: true,
    paper: "Chen et al., Nature 589.214",
    result: "2,032 km fibre trunk (Beijing–Jinan–Hefei–Shanghai, 32 trusted nodes, 135 links) integrated with Micius satellite to span 4,600 km; >150 users.",
    implies: "Formal peer-reviewed account of the full backbone. Establishes the scale, node count, per-link key rates (kbit/s class), and the trusted-node security model that bounds the end-to-end guarantee.",
  },
  {
    year: "2025",
    ref: "chen-npjqi-11-2025",
    inYaml: true,
    paper: "Chen et al., npj QI 11.137",
    result: "Carrier-grade expansion to >10,000 km; 145 backbone nodes, 144 links, 20 metropolitan sub-networks, 17 provinces, 80 cities.",
    implies: "Documents the operational phase beyond the 2017 trunk — a national QKD infrastructure built on the same trusted-relay architecture, now with standardised carrier-grade maintenance and monitoring.",
  },
];

---

<Infographic
  title="Beijing–Shanghai QKD backbone"
  description="The 2,032 km Beijing–Shanghai QKD trunk: prepare-and-measure decoy-state BB84 over 32 trusted-node relays, deployed by USTC and QuantumCTek and extended by the Micius satellite link for a 4,600 km space-ground span."
  references={[
    "chen-optexpress-17-2009",
    "chen-optexpress-18-2010",
    "chen-npjqi-7-2021",
    "chen-natphoton-2021-jingu",
    "chen-npjqi-11-2025",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="case-studies" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Beijing–Shanghai QKD backbone</h1>
        <p>
          The longest deployed terrestrial QKD network. Four-city fibre trunk
          carrying decoy-state BB84 keys between Beijing, Jinan, Hefei, and
          Shanghai through 32 trusted-relay nodes, declared operational in
          late 2017 and integrated with the Micius satellite to span 4,600 km
          between ground stations.
        </p>
        <dl class="hero-meta">
          <div><dt>Operator</dt><dd>USTC / Pan group · QuantumCTek (hardware) · state-sector users (finance, government)</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Location</dt><dd>Beijing ↔ Jinan ↔ Hefei ↔ Shanghai, China</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Year</dt><dd>Construction 2013–2016; operational 2017</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Technology</dt><dd>Prepare-and-measure decoy-state BB84 on polarisation-coded weak coherent pulses; trusted-node relay</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Scale</dt><dd>2,032 km trunk, 32 trusted relay nodes, 135 QKD links; satellite-linked to a 4,600 km integrated span</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Status</dt><dd>Operational</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Commercial model</dt><dd>Government-mandated infrastructure, sold as a key-distribution service to banks and ministries</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </header>

      <section id="what" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What it is</h2>
        <p>
          The backbone connects four cities with dedicated 1550 nm dark fibre.
          Each link runs decoy-state BB84 between QuantumCTek transmit and
          receive modules; at every trusted relay the keys are decrypted to
          classical bits, re-used for one-time-pad onward encryption, and
          handed to the next QKD module. The trust model rests on the physical
          security of the 32 relay nodes — not on quantum-mechanical
          guarantees between the endpoints. The trunk was integrated with the
          Micius low-Earth-orbit satellite in 2018, extending the reach of
          the same trusted-node architecture to a 4,600 km ground-station
          span through space-to-ground QKD downlinks.<SourceNote id="chen-natphoton-2021-jingu" />
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="papers" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Published papers</h2>
        <p>
          Every link on the backbone and its predecessor metro networks runs
          decoy-state BB84 over dark fibre with trusted relay at every node.
          The trust model is uniform throughout — the table records what each
          paper demonstrated and what it established for the deployments that
          followed.
        </p>
        <div class="exp-table-wrap">
        <table class="exp-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Paper</th>
              <th>Result</th>
              <th>What it implies</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {papers.map((p) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{p.year}</td>
                <td>{p.paper}{p.inYaml && <SourceNote id={p.ref} />}</td>
                <td>{p.result}</td>
                <td>{p.implies}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="verified" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Verified claims</h2>
        <ul class="claim-list">
          <li><strong>~2,032 km total length, four cities, 32 trusted nodes, 135 links</strong> — reported by USTC and confirmed in the integrated 4,600 km Nature paper.<SourceNote id="chen-natphoton-2021-jingu" /></li>
          <li><strong>Decoy-state BB84 with polarisation coding, QuantumCTek hardware</strong> — the deployment uses prepare-and-measure QKD, not entanglement distribution.<SourceNote id="chen-natphoton-2021-jingu" /></li>
          <li><strong>Trusted-relay architecture, not end-to-end secure.</strong> Each relay must be physically secured; compromise of a single node compromises the keys passing through it.</li>
          <li><strong>Operational user base.</strong> Reported users include the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the Bank of Communications, and government departments along the route — though throughput and uptime figures are not publicly audited.</li>
          <li><strong>4,600 km integrated span via Micius.</strong> The space-to-ground extension uses the Micius satellite as another trusted node, not an entanglement source for the trunk.<SourceNote id="chen-natphoton-2021-jingu" /></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="caveats" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Things to note</h2>
        <ul class="caveat-list">
          <li><strong>Not entanglement-based.</strong> The 2017 Micius satellite-to-ground entanglement-distribution result (Yin et al., <em>Science</em> 356.1140) is a separate experiment and is distinct from the trunk. The trunk itself is decoy-state BB84 — single-photon-level coherent pulses, not Bell pairs.</li>
          <li><strong>Not a "quantum internet".</strong> The backbone is a service for moving symmetric keys between endpoints; it does not transport quantum states or support distributed quantum-compute primitives.</li>
          <li><strong>Trusted-node security model.</strong> The end-to-end security depends on every one of the 32 trusted nodes; the information-theoretic guarantee of point-to-point QKD applies per link, not across the relayed path.</li>
          <li><strong>Throughput sits in the kbit/s range.</strong> Reported per-link key rates are in the kbit/s range over the longest hops, with ITS-style key buffering between sessions. The service is sized for symmetric-key replenishment rather than streaming.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="related" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Related entries</h2>
        <ul class="related-list">
          <li><a href={url("/applications")}>Applications</a> — QKD as one of several quantum-internet applications.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/repeaters")}>Quantum repeaters</a> — the entanglement-based architecture that would replace trusted nodes.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/links")}>Links</a> — the 0.2 dB/km fibre regime that bounds reach per hop.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/standards")}>Standards</a> — ITU-T and ETSI QKD-network standards the deployment aligns with.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/case-studies/epb")}>EPB Quantum Network</a> — the entanglement-based contrast.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/case-studies/bt-london")}>BT–Toshiba London QKD</a> — another commercial prepare-and-measure deployment, at metro scale.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

<style>
